The '''International Celestial Reference System''' ('''ICRS''') is the current standard [[celestial reference system]] adopted by the [[International Astronomical Union]] (IAU). Its origin is at the [[barycenter]] of the [[Solar System]], with axes that are intended to be "fixed" with respect to space. ICRS coordinates are approximately the same as [[equatorial coordinate system|equatorial coordinates]]: the mean pole at [[J2000]].0 in the ICRS lies at 17.3±0.2 [[milliarcsecond|mas]] in the direction 12 h and 5.1±0.2 mas in the direction 18 h. The mean [[equinox]] of J2000.0 is shifted from the ICRS [[right ascension]] origin by 78±10 mas (direct rotation around the polar axis).
The defining extragalactic reference frame of the ICRS is the [[International Celestial Reference Frame]] (currently ICRF2) based on hundreds of [[Astronomical radio source|extra-galactic radio sources]], mostly [[quasar]]s, distributed around the entire sky. Because they are so distant, they are apparently stationary to our current technology, yet their positions can be measured with the utmost accuracy by [[Very Long Baseline Interferometry]] (VLBI). The positions of most are known to 0.001 [[arc minute|arcsecond]] or better, which is orders of magnitude more precise than the best optical measurements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aa.usno.navy.mil/faq/docs/ICRS_doc.php |title=ICRS Narrative |accessdate=2012-06-07 | publisher=<!---http://aa.usno.navy.mil/index.php--->U.S. Naval Observatory Astronomical Applications}}</ref> At optical wavelengths, the ICRS is currently realized by the Hipparcos Celestial Reference Frame (HCRF), a subset of about 100,000 stars in the [[Hipparcos Catalogue]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://aa.usno.navy.mil/faq/docs/ICRS_doc.php#FROPT | title = International Celestial Reference System (ICRS) | publisher = U S Naval Observatory, Astronomical Applications Department | access-date = May 12, 2018 }}</ref> A more accurate optical realization of the ICRS (''Gaia''-CRF2), based on the observation by the [[Gaia (spacecraft)#Data releases|''Gaia'' spacecraft]] of almost 500,000 extragalactic objects believed to be quasars, is under preparation.<ref>{{ Citation | last = Gaia Collaboration | last2 = Mignard | first2 = F. | last3 = Klioner | first3 = S. | last4 = Lindegren | first4 = L. | last5 = et al | date = 2018 | title = ''Gaia'' Data Release 2. The celestial reference frame (''Gaia''-CRF2) | journal = Astronomy & Astrophysics | pages = | doi = 10.1051/0004-6361/201832916 | arxiv = 1804.09377 | accessdate = }}</ref><ref>{{ Citation | last = Lindegren | first = L. | last2 = Hernandez | first2 = J. | last3 = Bombrun | first3 = A. | last4 = Klioner | first4 = S. | last5 = et al | date = 2018 | title = ''Gaia'' Data Release 2 – The astrometric solution | journal = Astronomy & Astrophysics | volume = | issue = | pages = | doi = 10.1051/0004-6361/201832727 }}</ref>
